This paper deals with the problem of nonlinear interference mitigation in fiber-optic communication systems, which is a topic related to information theory (cs.IT). The proposed approach uses deep neural networks (cs.NE) to implement digital backpropagation (DBP), which is a technique commonly used in optical communication systems. The paper also discusses the training of the neural network, which involves optimizing a cost function (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper presents experimental results on a real-world fiber-optic link, which could be relevant to the field of optical networking (cs.OH). Finally, the paper uses natural language processing techniques to analyze the performance of the neural network, which could be relevant to the field of computational linguistics (cs.CL).
